4. How many players are there in each year, from 2000 to 2013? Do all teams have the same number of players?

To determine the number of players in each year we can use the table Salaries since it shows the salary of players by year. We can assume a player is in a year if it is getting paid that year. By selecting those observations between 2000 and 2013, grouping by year and counting the number of unique players in each year we can determine the number by year.

To find if all teams have the same number of players we should obtain first the number of players each team has which is open to interpretation. It can be the number of players per team as of the most current year, the number of players per team per year (2000 - 2013) or the number of players that have played for that team from 2000 to 2013.

For a meaningful path of analysis the number of players per team per year might be the best interpretation since we can then look at how teams have grown.

This task can be accomplished by pulling information from the Salaries table as well (it contains yearID, playerID, teamID). We use SQL query to obtain one table from each year that contains the number of member per team. Then we merge these tables by teamID to analyse the results

5. What team won the World Series in 2010? Include the name of the team, the league and division.

The table Teams contains yearID, name which contains the teams full name, lgID which contains the league, divID which has the teams division and WSWin which records if the team won the world series. In order to obtain the information needed, we select the name, lgID and divID columns, and pull the observation where yearID equals 10 and WSWin equals Y.

won_WS_2010 = dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT name, lgID, divID FROM Teams WHERE yearID = 2010 AND WSWin = 'Y'")
won_WS_2010
##                   name lgID divID
## 1 San Francisco Giants   NL     W

The team that won the World Series in 2010 is the San Francisco Giants.

6. What team lost the World Series each year? Again, include the name of the team, league and division.

This column WSWin in table Teams provides only who won and not who went and lost. Thus, we should find another way to determine the loser. Since the participants of the World Series are the champions of American League (AL in lgID) and National League (NA in lgID) according to Wikipedia, we can find the two champions of these two leages each year and select the one who did not win the World Series.

Useful columns are yearID, name which contains the teams full name, lgID which contains the league, divID which has the teams division, LgWin which tells if the team won the league and WSWin which records if the team won the world series.

WS_loser_by_year = dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT name, lgID, divID, yearID, LgWin, WSWin FROM Teams WHERE (WSWin = 'N' AND LgWin = 'Y' AND lgID = 'AL') OR (WSWin = 'N' AND LgWin = 'Y' AND lgID = 'NL') GROUP BY yearID")

7. Compute the table of World Series winners for all years, again with the name of the team, league and division.

In order to obtain this information we follow the same logic as in question 5, but this time we generalize it and group it by years.

The table Teams contains yearID, name which contains the teams full name, lgID which contains the league, divID which has the teams division and WSWin which records if the team won the world series. We should select the name, lgID and divID columns, pull the observation where WSWin equals Y and group by yearID since we cant the champion of each year.

10. In 2003, what were the three highest salaries? (We refer here to unique salaries, i.e., there may be several players getting the exact same amount.) Find the players who got any of these 3 salaries with all of their details?

The first thing we need to do is figure out what the three highest salaries are. Then we find who earned those salaries.

The table Salaries can help us find this answers. To get the highest three salaries we use the column salary from this table and order it by salary in decending order. We limit the results to 3 and use DISTINCT in the select statement to obtain only the three unique values that are the highest of all.

dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT DISTINCT salary FROM Salaries ORDER BY -salary LIMIT 3")
##    salary
## 1 3.3e+07
## 2 3.2e+07
## 3 3.0e+07

Once we have found these we can use them in combination with tables Master and Salaries to see who earned those salaries. The table Master will provide useful information on the demografict of the players as long as we choose the correct columns. On the other hand we will use the table Salaries only for the column salary. In one query we can obtain some of the data needed for all players with the help of joining tables matching by column playerID and indicating the specific values of salaries.

11. For 2010, compute the total payroll of each of the different teams. Next compute the team payrolls for all years in the database for which we have salary information. Display these in a plot.

13. Compare payrolls for the teams that are in the same leagues, and then in the same divisions. Are there any interesting characteristics? Have certain teams always had top payrolls over the years? Is there a connection between payroll and performance?

To answer this question we can compute the total salaries that players in those teams won across all years and then focus separatly in the league and division separation when we plot them. This will help us identify if there re meaningful differences in the big picture.

Since division information has to be obtain from another table we use table teams and merge with the table containing salary and teamID information through teamID to match the division of each team.

To address the next part of this question we can look at the teams with the top 6 salaries of each year and count the occurances of each.

Finally to measure performance we can use the variable w containing the number of wins a team has each year. If we sum the wins a team has overall we can compare it with its overall payroll to see if we can identify a relationship or trend.
